<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="195" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,325,1576]" pageId="4" pageNumber="195">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,345,433,459]" pageId="4" pageNumber="195">Description.</emphasis>
<typeStatus box="[354,458,434,460]" pageId="4" pageNumber="195">Holotype</typeStatus>
complete (ECOSUR-250), mature female. Body colorless, 
<quantity box="[1143,1223,434,460]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.1" pageId="4" pageNumber="195" unit="mm" value="11.0">11 mm</quantity>
long, 
<quantity box="[1298,1366,434,460]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.0" pageId="4" pageNumber="195" unit="mm" value="2.0">2 mm</quantity>
wide, with three parathoracic segments, 28 abdominal segments, caudal peduncle 
<quantity box="[1001,1066,470,496]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.0" pageId="4" pageNumber="195" unit="mm" value="3.0">3 mm</quantity>
long (
<figureCitation box="[1138,1203,470,496]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1864,1888]" captionTargetBox="[193,1395,352,1838]" captionTargetId="figure-236@2.[193,1395,352,1838]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. Idanthyrsus bastidai n. sp. (ECOSUR-250). A, Holotype complete specimen. B, Anterior region, dorsal view. C, Anterior region, lateral view. D, Thorax and parathorax, lateral view. E, Opercular peduncle, ventral view. F, Abdominal region, ventral view. Scale bars: A–C: 1 mm, D–F: 0.5 mm. Abbreviations: ab8, abdominal neuropodia segment 8; bo, building organ; cn1, cirrus neuropodia segment 1; ll2, lateral lamellae segment 2; mo, median organ; mr, median ridge; ne, parathoracic neuropodia; no, parathoracic notopodia; tf, tentacular filaments." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5551977" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5551977/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="195">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,325,1576]" pageId="4" pageNumber="195">
Opercular crown and opercular stalk completely divided into two lobes (
<figureCitation box="[1026,1150,506,532]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1864,1888]" captionTargetBox="[193,1395,352,1838]" captionTargetId="figure-236@2.[193,1395,352,1838]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. Idanthyrsus bastidai n. sp. (ECOSUR-250). A, Holotype complete specimen. B, Anterior region, dorsal view. C, Anterior region, lateral view. D, Thorax and parathorax, lateral view. E, Opercular peduncle, ventral view. F, Abdominal region, ventral view. Scale bars: A–C: 1 mm, D–F: 0.5 mm. Abbreviations: ab8, abdominal neuropodia segment 8; bo, building organ; cn1, cirrus neuropodia segment 1; ll2, lateral lamellae segment 2; mo, median organ; mr, median ridge; ne, parathoracic neuropodia; no, parathoracic notopodia; tf, tentacular filaments." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5551977" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5551977/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="195">Fig. 1A–B</figureCitation>
). Opercular disc oblique, two rows of light amber paleae; outer row with 25 paleae per lobe, inner row with ~18 paleae per lobe. Outer paleae straight, marginal spines long, thin, progressively larger distally; 20–30 pairs of lateral spines. Paleal anterior region with compact thecae with irregular margins. Blade slightly inclined at an angle of 170° (
<figureCitation box="[1153,1278,614,640]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1924,1948]" captionTargetBox="[219,1368,181,1900]" captionTargetId="figure-18@3.[219,1368,181,1900]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 2. Idanthyrsus bastidai n. sp. (ECOSUR-250). A–B, Outer palea. C, Inner palea. D, Tip of inner palea. E, Abdominal neurochaetae. F, Abdominal uncini. G, Paratype with fragments of tubes (ECOSUR-251). H, Nuchal hook of another paratype. Scale bars: A–C, E: 100 µm; D: 20 µm; F: 10 µm; G: 1 mm. Abbreviation: Li, limbation." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5551979" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5551979/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="195">Fig. 2A–B</figureCitation>
). Inner paleae cylindrical, slightly inclined, tapered; blade with transverse thecae (
<figureCitation box="[909,998,650,676]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1924,1948]" captionTargetBox="[219,1368,181,1900]" captionTargetId="figure-18@3.[219,1368,181,1900]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 2. Idanthyrsus bastidai n. sp. (ECOSUR-250). A–B, Outer palea. C, Inner palea. D, Tip of inner palea. E, Abdominal neurochaetae. F, Abdominal uncini. G, Paratype with fragments of tubes (ECOSUR-251). H, Nuchal hook of another paratype. Scale bars: A–C, E: 100 µm; D: 20 µm; F: 10 µm; G: 1 mm. Abbreviation: Li, limbation." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5551979" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5551979/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="195">Fig. 2C</figureCitation>
); tip smooth, blunt (
<figureCitation box="[1224,1315,650,676]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1924,1948]" captionTargetBox="[219,1368,181,1900]" captionTargetId="figure-18@3.[219,1368,181,1900]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 2. Idanthyrsus bastidai n. sp. (ECOSUR-250). A–B, Outer palea. C, Inner palea. D, Tip of inner palea. E, Abdominal neurochaetae. F, Abdominal uncini. G, Paratype with fragments of tubes (ECOSUR-251). H, Nuchal hook of another paratype. Scale bars: A–C, E: 100 µm; D: 20 µm; F: 10 µm; G: 1 mm. Abbreviation: Li, limbation." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5551979" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5551979/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="195">Fig. 2D</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,325,1576]" pageId="4" pageNumber="195">
Opercular peduncle colorless (
<figureCitation box="[538,660,686,712]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1864,1888]" captionTargetBox="[193,1395,352,1838]" captionTargetId="figure-236@2.[193,1395,352,1838]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. Idanthyrsus bastidai n. sp. (ECOSUR-250). A, Holotype complete specimen. B, Anterior region, dorsal view. C, Anterior region, lateral view. D, Thorax and parathorax, lateral view. E, Opercular peduncle, ventral view. F, Abdominal region, ventral view. Scale bars: A–C: 1 mm, D–F: 0.5 mm. Abbreviations: ab8, abdominal neuropodia segment 8; bo, building organ; cn1, cirrus neuropodia segment 1; ll2, lateral lamellae segment 2; mo, median organ; mr, median ridge; ne, parathoracic neuropodia; no, parathoracic notopodia; tf, tentacular filaments." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5551977" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5551977/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="195">Fig. 1A–C</figureCitation>
). Two amber nuchal hooks on the left lobe, one hook on the right (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1864,1888]" captionTargetBox="[193,1395,352,1838]" captionTargetId="figure-236@2.[193,1395,352,1838]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. Idanthyrsus bastidai n. sp. (ECOSUR-250). A, Holotype complete specimen. B, Anterior region, dorsal view. C, Anterior region, lateral view. D, Thorax and parathorax, lateral view. E, Opercular peduncle, ventral view. F, Abdominal region, ventral view. Scale bars: A–C: 1 mm, D–F: 0.5 mm. Abbreviations: ab8, abdominal neuropodia segment 8; bo, building organ; cn1, cirrus neuropodia segment 1; ll2, lateral lamellae segment 2; mo, median organ; mr, median ridge; ne, parathoracic neuropodia; no, parathoracic notopodia; tf, tentacular filaments." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5551977" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5551977/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="195">Fig. 1B</figureCitation>
). Nuchal hooks falcate, with long limbation, tip sharp (
<figureCitation box="[806,897,722,748]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1924,1948]" captionTargetBox="[219,1368,181,1900]" captionTargetId="figure-18@3.[219,1368,181,1900]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 2. Idanthyrsus bastidai n. sp. (ECOSUR-250). A–B, Outer palea. C, Inner palea. D, Tip of inner palea. E, Abdominal neurochaetae. F, Abdominal uncini. G, Paratype with fragments of tubes (ECOSUR-251). H, Nuchal hook of another paratype. Scale bars: A–C, E: 100 µm; D: 20 µm; F: 10 µm; G: 1 mm. Abbreviation: Li, limbation." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5551979" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5551979/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="195">Fig. 2H</figureCitation>
). Tentacles and palps colorless. Median ridge as long as opercular stalk, with marginal brown eyespots. Median organ small, conical, colorless, without eyespots (
<figureCitation box="[160,245,794,820]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1864,1888]" captionTargetBox="[193,1395,352,1838]" captionTargetId="figure-236@2.[193,1395,352,1838]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. Idanthyrsus bastidai n. sp. (ECOSUR-250). A, Holotype complete specimen. B, Anterior region, dorsal view. C, Anterior region, lateral view. D, Thorax and parathorax, lateral view. E, Opercular peduncle, ventral view. F, Abdominal region, ventral view. Scale bars: A–C: 1 mm, D–F: 0.5 mm. Abbreviations: ab8, abdominal neuropodia segment 8; bo, building organ; cn1, cirrus neuropodia segment 1; ll2, lateral lamellae segment 2; mo, median organ; mr, median ridge; ne, parathoracic neuropodia; no, parathoracic notopodia; tf, tentacular filaments." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5551977" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5551977/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="195">Fig. 1E</figureCitation>
). Building organ with small brownish spots.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,325,1576]" pageId="4" pageNumber="195">Thorax without notochaetae. Chaetiger 1 with a pair of neuropodia bearing capillary, pinnate chaetae. Chaetiger 2 with capillary neurochaetae, a pair of lateral small cirri, and branchiae.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,325,1576]" pageId="4" pageNumber="195">
Parathorax colorless with three segments, all with paired branchiae (
<figureCitation box="[961,1083,902,928]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1864,1888]" captionTargetBox="[193,1395,352,1838]" captionTargetId="figure-236@2.[193,1395,352,1838]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. Idanthyrsus bastidai n. sp. (ECOSUR-250). A, Holotype complete specimen. B, Anterior region, dorsal view. C, Anterior region, lateral view. D, Thorax and parathorax, lateral view. E, Opercular peduncle, ventral view. F, Abdominal region, ventral view. Scale bars: A–C: 1 mm, D–F: 0.5 mm. Abbreviations: ab8, abdominal neuropodia segment 8; bo, building organ; cn1, cirrus neuropodia segment 1; ll2, lateral lamellae segment 2; mo, median organ; mr, median ridge; ne, parathoracic neuropodia; no, parathoracic notopodia; tf, tentacular filaments." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5551977" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5551977/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="195">Fig. 1C–D</figureCitation>
). Notopodia with six lanceolate and seven pectinate chaetae. Neurochaetae lanceolate and capillaries, thinner than notochaetae.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,325,1576]" pageId="4" pageNumber="195">
Abdominal segments colorless, with a pair of branchiae decreasing in size towards segment 16. Neuropodia with verticillate chaetae (
<figureCitation box="[439,528,1010,1036]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1924,1948]" captionTargetBox="[219,1368,181,1900]" captionTargetId="figure-18@3.[219,1368,181,1900]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 2. Idanthyrsus bastidai n. sp. (ECOSUR-250). A–B, Outer palea. C, Inner palea. D, Tip of inner palea. E, Abdominal neurochaetae. F, Abdominal uncini. G, Paratype with fragments of tubes (ECOSUR-251). H, Nuchal hook of another paratype. Scale bars: A–C, E: 100 µm; D: 20 µm; F: 10 µm; G: 1 mm. Abbreviation: Li, limbation." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5551979" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5551979/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="195">Fig. 2E</figureCitation>
). Notopodia with a series of uncini with 6–7 transverse rows of teeth (
<figureCitation box="[1336,1423,1010,1036]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1924,1948]" captionTargetBox="[219,1368,181,1900]" captionTargetId="figure-18@3.[219,1368,181,1900]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 2. Idanthyrsus bastidai n. sp. (ECOSUR-250). A–B, Outer palea. C, Inner palea. D, Tip of inner palea. E, Abdominal neurochaetae. F, Abdominal uncini. G, Paratype with fragments of tubes (ECOSUR-251). H, Nuchal hook of another paratype. Scale bars: A–C, E: 100 µm; D: 20 µm; F: 10 µm; G: 1 mm. Abbreviation: Li, limbation." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5551979" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5551979/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="195">Fig. 2F</figureCitation>
). Abdominal segment eight with longer neurochaetae (
<figureCitation box="[746,830,1046,1072]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1864,1888]" captionTargetBox="[193,1395,352,1838]" captionTargetId="figure-236@2.[193,1395,352,1838]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. Idanthyrsus bastidai n. sp. (ECOSUR-250). A, Holotype complete specimen. B, Anterior region, dorsal view. C, Anterior region, lateral view. D, Thorax and parathorax, lateral view. E, Opercular peduncle, ventral view. F, Abdominal region, ventral view. Scale bars: A–C: 1 mm, D–F: 0.5 mm. Abbreviations: ab8, abdominal neuropodia segment 8; bo, building organ; cn1, cirrus neuropodia segment 1; ll2, lateral lamellae segment 2; mo, median organ; mr, median ridge; ne, parathoracic neuropodia; no, parathoracic notopodia; tf, tentacular filaments." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5551977" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5551977/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="195">Fig. 1F</figureCitation>
). Caudal peduncle cylindrical, colorless (
<figureCitation box="[1294,1383,1046,1072]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1864,1888]" captionTargetBox="[193,1395,352,1838]" captionTargetId="figure-236@2.[193,1395,352,1838]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. Idanthyrsus bastidai n. sp. (ECOSUR-250). A, Holotype complete specimen. B, Anterior region, dorsal view. C, Anterior region, lateral view. D, Thorax and parathorax, lateral view. E, Opercular peduncle, ventral view. F, Abdominal region, ventral view. Scale bars: A–C: 1 mm, D–F: 0.5 mm. Abbreviations: ab8, abdominal neuropodia segment 8; bo, building organ; cn1, cirrus neuropodia segment 1; ll2, lateral lamellae segment 2; mo, median organ; mr, median ridge; ne, parathoracic neuropodia; no, parathoracic notopodia; tf, tentacular filaments." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5551977" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5551977/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="195">Fig. 1A</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,325,1576]" pageId="4" pageNumber="195">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,312,1081,1107]" pageId="4" pageNumber="195">Variation</emphasis>
. Body 
<quantity box="[396,504,1082,1108]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="8.0" metricValueMax="12.0" metricValueMin="4.0" pageId="4" pageNumber="195" unit="mm" value="8.0" valueMax="12.0" valueMin="4.0">4–12 mm</quantity>
in total length, 
<quantity box="[686,801,1082,1108]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.4" metricValueMax="2.0" metricValueMin="0.8" pageId="4" pageNumber="195" unit="mm" value="1.4" valueMax="2.0" valueMin="0.8">0.8–2 mm</quantity>
wide, 18–33 abdominal segments, caudal peduncle 
<quantity metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.5" metricValueMax="4.0" metricValueMin="1.0" pageId="4" pageNumber="195" unit="mm" value="2.5" valueMax="4.0" valueMin="1.0">1–4 mm</quantity>
. Opercular crown made of 10–33 outer paleae per lobe, and 8–19 inner paleae per lobe. Almost all specimens with one pair of hooks (
<figureCitation box="[418,509,1154,1180]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1924,1948]" captionTargetBox="[219,1368,181,1900]" captionTargetId="figure-18@3.[219,1368,181,1900]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 2. Idanthyrsus bastidai n. sp. (ECOSUR-250). A–B, Outer palea. C, Inner palea. D, Tip of inner palea. E, Abdominal neurochaetae. F, Abdominal uncini. G, Paratype with fragments of tubes (ECOSUR-251). H, Nuchal hook of another paratype. Scale bars: A–C, E: 100 µm; D: 20 µm; F: 10 µm; G: 1 mm. Abbreviation: Li, limbation." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5551979" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5551979/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="195">Fig. 2H</figureCitation>
), except for five bearing an extra hook on one side, including the 
<typeStatus box="[1245,1347,1154,1180]" pageId="4" pageNumber="195">holotype</typeStatus>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,325,1576]" box="[199,1118,1190,1216]" pageId="4" pageNumber="195">
One 
<typeStatus box="[253,349,1190,1216]" pageId="4" pageNumber="195">paratype</typeStatus>
specimen with fragments of the tube made of coarse sand (
<figureCitation box="[1015,1105,1190,1216]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1924,1948]" captionTargetBox="[219,1368,181,1900]" captionTargetId="figure-18@3.[219,1368,181,1900]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 2. Idanthyrsus bastidai n. sp. (ECOSUR-250). A–B, Outer palea. C, Inner palea. D, Tip of inner palea. E, Abdominal neurochaetae. F, Abdominal uncini. G, Paratype with fragments of tubes (ECOSUR-251). H, Nuchal hook of another paratype. Scale bars: A–C, E: 100 µm; D: 20 µm; F: 10 µm; G: 1 mm. Abbreviation: Li, limbation." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5551979" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5551979/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="195">Fig. 2G</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="195" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,325,1576]" pageId="4" pageNumber="195">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,1226,1252]" pageId="4" pageNumber="195">Etymology.</emphasis>
This species is named after Dr. J. Rolando Bastida Zavala, for being a great mentor and teaching me about the world of polychaetes. The species name is a noun in the genitive case (
<bibRefCitation author="ICZN &amp; International Commission on Zoological Nomenclature" box="[1095,1228,1262,1288]" pageId="4" pageNumber="195" refId="ref13655" refString="ICZN [International Commission on Zoological Nomenclature] (1999) International Code of Zoological Nomenclature. 4 th Edition. International Trust for Zoological Nomenclature in association with the British Museum (Natural History), London. 306 pp. [http: // www. iczn. org / iczn / index. jsp]" type="book" year="1999">ICZN 1999</bibRefCitation>
, Art. 31.1.2).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[199,1265,1297,1325]" pageId="4" pageNumber="195" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,325,1576]" box="[199,1265,1297,1325]" pageId="4" pageNumber="195">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,353,1297,1323]" pageId="4" pageNumber="195">Distribution.</emphasis>
Turpialito, Cumaná, 
<collectingCountry box="[591,706,1298,1324]" name="Venezuela" pageId="4" pageNumber="195">Venezuela</collectingCountry>
at 
<quantity box="[741,805,1298,1325]" metricMagnitude="0" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.5" pageId="4" pageNumber="195" unit="m" value="1.5">1.5 m</quantity>
depth. Associated with 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Linnaeus" authorityYear="1758" box="[1073,1185,1298,1324]" class="Hydrozoa" family="Milleporidae" genus="Millepora" kingdom="Animalia" order="Anthoathecata" pageId="4" pageNumber="195" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1073,1185,1298,1324]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="195">Millepora</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
corals.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="195" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,325,1576]" pageId="4" pageNumber="195">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,308,1334,1360]" pageId="4" pageNumber="195">Remarks</emphasis>
. 
<taxonomicName authority="Chávez-López, 2021" authorityName="Chávez-López" authorityYear="2021" box="[322,551,1334,1360]" class="Polychaeta" family="Sabellariidae" genus="Idanthyrsus" kingdom="Animalia" pageId="4" pageNumber="195" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="bastidai" status="n. sp.">
<emphasis box="[322,551,1334,1360]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="195">Idanthyrsus bastidai</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[558,620,1334,1360]" pageId="4" pageNumber="195">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[558,620,1334,1360]" pageId="4" pageNumber="195" rank="species">n. sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
closely resembles 
<taxonomicName box="[832,1003,1334,1360]" class="Polychaeta" family="Sabellariidae" genus="Idanthyrsus" kingdom="Animalia" pageId="4" pageNumber="195" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="undetermined">
<emphasis box="[832,964,1334,1360]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="195">Idanthyrsus</emphasis>
sp.
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis box="[1010,1052,1334,1360]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="195">fide</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Chavez-Lopez, Y." box="[1059,1304,1334,1360]" pageId="4" pageNumber="195" refId="ref13048" refString="Chavez-Lopez, Y. (2019) Revision faunistica de los gusanos panal (Polychaeta: Sabellariidae) del Pacifico oriental tropical. Thesis, Universidad del Mar, Puerto Angel, 148 pp." type="book" year="2019">Chávez-López (2019)</bibRefCitation>
from 
<collectingRegion country="Mexico" name="Guerrero" pageId="4" pageNumber="195">Guerrero</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[212,301,1370,1396]" name="Mexico" pageId="4" pageNumber="195">Mexico</collectingCountry>
. Both species have outer paleae with long, thin, straight spines; however, 
<taxonomicName box="[1150,1324,1370,1396]" class="Polychaeta" family="Sabellariidae" genus="Idanthyrsus" kingdom="Animalia" pageId="4" pageNumber="195" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="undetermined">
<emphasis box="[1150,1282,1370,1396]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="195">Idanthyrsus</emphasis>
sp.
</taxonomicName>
has completely straight outer paleae and blunt nuchal hooks (
<bibRefCitation author="Chavez-Lopez, Y." box="[751,984,1406,1432]" pageId="4" pageNumber="195" refId="ref13048" refString="Chavez-Lopez, Y. (2019) Revision faunistica de los gusanos panal (Polychaeta: Sabellariidae) del Pacifico oriental tropical. Thesis, Universidad del Mar, Puerto Angel, 148 pp." type="book" year="2019">Chávez-López 2019</bibRefCitation>
: 
<figureCitation box="[996,1113,1406,1432]" captionStart="FIGURE 9" captionStartId="16.[151,250,1545,1569]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,181,1521]" captionTargetId="figure-31@16.[151,1435,181,1521]" captionTargetPageId="16" captionText="FIGURE 9. Sabellaria salazari n. sp. Holotype (ECOSUR-254). A. Anterior region, dorsal view. B, Anterior region, right lateral view. C, Anterior region, ventral view. D, Opercular crown, dorsal view. E, Nuchal spines. F, Median ridge, and median organ, non-type specimen (ECOSUR-P3207). Scale bars: A–D: 0.5 mm, E–F: 0.2 mm. Abbreviations: mo, median organ; mr, median ridge." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5551993" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5551993/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="195">Fig. 9C, F</figureCitation>
) with limbation shorter than that in 
<taxonomicName authority="Chávez-López, 2021" authorityName="Chávez-López" authorityYear="2021" box="[228,341,1442,1468]" class="Polychaeta" family="Sabellariidae" genus="Idanthyrsus" kingdom="Animalia" pageId="4" pageNumber="195" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="bastidai" status="n. sp.">
<emphasis box="[228,341,1442,1468]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="195">I. bastidai</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[348,411,1442,1468]" pageId="4" pageNumber="195">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[348,411,1442,1468]" pageId="4" pageNumber="195" rank="species">n. sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
that is characterized by slightly bent outer paleae (
<figureCitation box="[978,1099,1442,1468]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1924,1948]" captionTargetBox="[219,1368,181,1900]" captionTargetId="figure-18@3.[219,1368,181,1900]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 2. Idanthyrsus bastidai n. sp. (ECOSUR-250). A–B, Outer palea. C, Inner palea. D, Tip of inner palea. E, Abdominal neurochaetae. F, Abdominal uncini. G, Paratype with fragments of tubes (ECOSUR-251). H, Nuchal hook of another paratype. Scale bars: A–C, E: 100 µm; D: 20 µm; F: 10 µm; G: 1 mm. Abbreviation: Li, limbation." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5551979" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5551979/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="195">Fig. 2A–B</figureCitation>
) and sharp nuchal hooks (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1924,1948]" captionTargetBox="[219,1368,181,1900]" captionTargetId="figure-18@3.[219,1368,181,1900]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 2. Idanthyrsus bastidai n. sp. (ECOSUR-250). A–B, Outer palea. C, Inner palea. D, Tip of inner palea. E, Abdominal neurochaetae. F, Abdominal uncini. G, Paratype with fragments of tubes (ECOSUR-251). H, Nuchal hook of another paratype. Scale bars: A–C, E: 100 µm; D: 20 µm; F: 10 µm; G: 1 mm. Abbreviation: Li, limbation." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5551979" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5551979/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="195">Fig. 2H</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,325,1576]" pageId="4" pageNumber="195">
The coloration pattern also differs in both species, while 
<taxonomicName box="[834,1005,1514,1540]" class="Polychaeta" family="Sabellariidae" genus="Idanthyrsus" kingdom="Animalia" pageId="4" pageNumber="195" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="undetermined">
<emphasis box="[834,966,1514,1540]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="195">Idanthyrsus</emphasis>
sp.
</taxonomicName>
has the opercular peduncle and thorax strongly pigmented (
<bibRefCitation author="Chavez-Lopez, Y." box="[383,615,1550,1576]" pageId="4" pageNumber="195" refId="ref13048" refString="Chavez-Lopez, Y. (2019) Revision faunistica de los gusanos panal (Polychaeta: Sabellariidae) del Pacifico oriental tropical. Thesis, Universidad del Mar, Puerto Angel, 148 pp." type="book" year="2019">Chávez-López 2019</bibRefCitation>
), 
<taxonomicName authority="Chávez-López, 2021" authorityName="Chávez-López" authorityYear="2021" box="[634,747,1550,1576]" class="Polychaeta" family="Sabellariidae" genus="Idanthyrsus" kingdom="Animalia" pageId="4" pageNumber="195" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="bastidai" status="n. sp.">
<emphasis box="[634,747,1550,1576]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="195">I. bastidai</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[755,817,1550,1576]" pageId="4" pageNumber="195">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[755,817,1550,1576]" pageId="4" pageNumber="195" rank="species">n. sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
lacks apparent pigmentation (
<figureCitation box="[1156,1279,1550,1576]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1864,1888]" captionTargetBox="[193,1395,352,1838]" captionTargetId="figure-236@2.[193,1395,352,1838]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. Idanthyrsus bastidai n. sp. (ECOSUR-250). A, Holotype complete specimen. B, Anterior region, dorsal view. C, Anterior region, lateral view. D, Thorax and parathorax, lateral view. E, Opercular peduncle, ventral view. F, Abdominal region, ventral view. Scale bars: A–C: 1 mm, D–F: 0.5 mm. Abbreviations: ab8, abdominal neuropodia segment 8; bo, building organ; cn1, cirrus neuropodia segment 1; ll2, lateral lamellae segment 2; mo, median organ; mr, median ridge; ne, parathoracic neuropodia; no, parathoracic notopodia; tf, tentacular filaments." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5551977" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5551977/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="195">Fig. 1A–C</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
